  "prompt": "Who is DC's worst street-level character and why?",
  "response": "Defining \"worst\" in terms of a character can be subjective and depends on the criteria used (e.g., writing quality, popularity, or perceived impact). However, one street-level DC character often cited as underwhelming or poorly received is **Dogwelder**, a member of Section 8 from *Hitman*. \n\nDogwelder's premise is intentionally absurd and grotesque\u2014he \"welds\" dead dogs to people's faces as a form of vigilante justice. While the character is meant to be a darkly comedic satire of superhero tropes, many fans and critics find him distasteful, overly gimmicky, or simply unfunny. His inclusion in the DC universe often feels jarring and out of place, even within the context of the intentionally bizarre Section 8 team.\n\nHowever, it's worth noting that Dogwelder's \"worst\" status is partially by design, as the character and his team were created to parody the excesses and oddities of superhero comics. If \"worst\" is defined by narrative depth, relatability, or mainstream appeal, Dogwelder arguably fits the bill, but he also serves a unique (if niche) purpose in DC's broader storytelling.",
